{
  "doc_id": "8960",
  "text": "This greater adsorption affinity of CO 2 in shales compared to CH 4 and the corresponding methane replacement by the injected CO 2 has an additional advantage for the process through the storage of substantial amounts of CO 2 in shale plays, therefore contributing to the mitigation of atmospheric CO 2 levels and ultimately assisting in overcoming global warming. For example, up to around 171 billion tonnes of CO 2 can be stored in the Marcellus Shale in the Appalachian Basin [CITATION_1] and up to around 28 billion tonnes in the Devonian shales in Kentucky [CITATION_2] . According to the prediction of Liu et al. [CITATION_3] based on reservoir modelling, around 4 × 10 4 tonnes of CO 2 can be injected through each horizontal well into the New Albany Shale play with less than 1% breakthrough, of which 95% of the CO 2 can be sequestrated in the shale play. Therefore, the use of a greenhouse gas such as CO 2 in the hydro fracturing process will assist in protecting the environment by reducing the greenhouse gas effect and will also lead to additional shale gas production enhancement.",
